How To Use
**********


 @{" Menus " Link "Menus"} 
 @{" Gadgets " Link "Gadgets"} 
 @{" Tooltypes " Link "Tooltypes"} 


@EndNode

@Node "Menus" "IR-SlaveE.guide/Menus"
@Next "Gadgets"
@Toc "How To Use"

Menus
=====

Project
-------

@{i}New@{ui}
     Deletes all the commands. A new project can be edited.

@{i}Load...@{ui}
     Loads an already existing project.

@{i}Save@{ui}
     Saves the actually edited project with the current name.

@{i}Save as...@{ui}
     Saves the actually edited project. The path/name can be given via
     a filerequester.

@{i}Info...@{ui}
     Gives some information about the authors and the project.

@{i}Hide@{ui}
     Closes the GUI of the IR-Slave. Although the IR-Slave stays
     active. To reopen the GUI use commodities exchange.

@{i}Quit@{ui}
     Quits the IR-Slave.

Edit
----

@{i}New@{ui}
     Creates a new ir-command-entry. In the "name"-gadget you can name
     this function - like "Tv set, power".

     In the action-gadget you can type a command to be executed when
     the specific ir signal is recognized. This line will be
     interpreted like a command line in the shell.

@{i}Cut@{ui}
     The current entry will be cut to an internal buffer and can be
     inserted anywhere (with paste).

@{i}Copy@{ui}
     Does the same as @{i}cut@{ui} - the current entry stays in the list.

@{i}Paste@{ui}
     The entry in the internal buffer will be inserted in the command
     list.

@{i}Sort@{ui}
     The command list will be sorted.


@EndNode

@Node "Gadgets" "IR-SlaveE.guide/Gadgets"
@Next "Tooltypes"
@Prev "Menus"
@Toc "How To Use"

Gadgets
=======

Commands
--------

@{i}List@{ui}
     Here, all the commands are listed by name. A '-' in front of the
     name means, that no ir-code is learned for this command.

@{i}Learn@{ui}
     Use this gadget to assign an ir-code to an entry in the command
     list. Whenever the ir-signal is recognized by the hardware (and
     watching is enabled) the relating command will be executed.  See
     @{"IR-Learning" Link "IR-Learning"}.

     After learning, the received ir data will be displayed.

@{i}Name@{ui}
     Here you can type any name - this will help you to remember which
     command is assigned to which ir code.

@{i}Action/Test@{ui}
     In this string gadget you can type a command line which will be
     executed whenever the specific infra red signal is recognized by
     the IR-Slave hardware (or by pressing the test gadget). This
     string will be interpreted as a command line typed in a shell.

Configuration
-------------

@{i}Protocol@{ui}
     In this gadget you can type a file name for the protocol file of
     received ir signals.

@{i}Tolerance@{ui}
     The higher this value is the exacter the received ir signal and
     the lerned signal must match. Values between 5 and 8 should work
     fine.

@{i}Code@{ui}
     The half code is an optimized way to store the ir-data. This
     format is faster but does not work with all remote controls. So
     you should simply try if it works.

@{i}Watching@{ui}
     If "watching" is switched on, the ir-slave recognizes ir signals.
     This works only when all ir-commands are learned.

@{i}Rate@{ui}
     A high rate means that the hardware is checked very often for
     incoming ir signals. A low rate means that the hardware is not
     checked so often - uses less cpu power.


@EndNode

@Node "Tooltypes" "IR-SlaveE.guide/Tooltypes"
@Prev "Gadgets"
@Toc "How To Use"

Tooltypes
=========

   If you start the ir slave by doubleclick the tooltypes of its icon
will be used. If you doubleclick on a project (or shift doubleclick it)
the tooltypes of the project will be used.

   If you start the ir slave from the shell, you can use the same
arguments as the tooltypes.
E.g. @{b}1> IR-Slave demos/demo1.slaved CX_POPUP=NO CX_POPKEY=f10@{ub}

   The following tooltypes are supported:

CX_POPUP=
    YES
          open GUI on startup

    NO
          start hidden

CX_POPKEY=
     Key on which the GUI should pop up. e.g. @{b}control s@{ub} default ist
     @{b}lalt esc@{ub}

PUBSCREEN=
     Name of a public screen which should be prefered for the GUI.

LEFT=
     Left edge of the gui window.

TOP=
     Top edge of the gui window.

RATE=
     See @{"Gadgets" Link "Gadgets"}.

TOLERANCE=
     See @{"Gadgets" Link "Gadgets"}, and  @{"IR-Learning" Link "IR-Learning"}.

OUTPUT=
     Protocol file. See @{"Gadgets" Link "Gadgets"}, and @{"IR-Learning" Link "IR-Learning"}.

PROTOCOL=
    YES
          Echo all the received signals and report executed commands.

    NO
          Do create a log flie.

PROJECT=
     Only in the IR-Slave icon: Datafile which should be loaded on
     startup.


@EndNode

@Node "Hardware" "IR-SlaveE.guide/Hardware"
@Next "IR-Learning"
@Prev "How To Use"
@Toc "Main"

Hardware
********

Gerneral Information
====================

   The hardware consists of a receiver unit which is half SMD (surface
mounted device). The hardware is connected to the joystickport. The
hardware can only be ordered by the authors - See @{"Registering" Link "Registering"}. You may
order either documents for the hardware, the construction kit without
PCB, the contruction kit with PCB or the complete hardware.

   If you want to order a construction kit you should have some
experience with this electronical stuff! Although you need not be a
profi...

   The hardware works with all remote controls which have a pulse
frequency between 30kHz and 40kHz and with a minimum impulse length of
20Ąs (Philips, Blaupunkt, Panasonic etc.).  If you want to know if
your remote control will work with the ir-slave simply contact one of
the authors (J³rgen Frank).

   The range of the ir slave is about 4-6m depending on your remote
control.

   The IR-Slave is compatible to the IR-Master (also by J³rgen Frank &
Michael Watzl). They can be used both on a Y-Adapter.

Trouble shooting
================

   If your hardware won't work after it is finished so this may have
one of the following reasons:

Error in the construction
     Check cable, connectors and components

Receiver to near to an interfearing field like a monitor, bright light, etc.
     Place the received to a sheltered place.

Amiga learns badly or not at all
     Batteries in the remote control are too weak


@EndNode

@Node "IR-Learning" "IR-SlaveE.guide/IR-Learning"
@Next "Appendix"
@Prev "Hardware"
@Toc "Main"

IR-Learning
***********

  1. Choose an entry in the list

  2. Click on "learn"
     ==> the pointer will be frozen

  3. Aim with your remote control on the sensor of the ir slave
     hardware. The distance should be about the half of the distance in
     the later use. So if you normally lie on your couch 4 meters away
     from your amiga - you shoul learn the commands with a distance of
     2 meters.

  4. Press the button on the remote control and hold it down until the
     ir slave has recognized the signal. If you press the right mouse
     button the learn action will be cancelled.

   @{i}Important notes@{ui}

   @{b}*@{ub} It is possible that the ir-slave will not react on your actions
     the first time. In this case you should test the ir-slave with
     other remote controls an try other values for tolerance and rate.

   @{b}*@{ub} Successful learning depends on the distance. So if it does not
     work fine you should try relearning in different distances between
     1 and 2 meters.

   @{b}*@{ub} If the batteries of the remote control are weak the ir signal is
     not very exact. This can lead to a incomplete learned ir signal.
     The ir slave won't recognize the signals correctly.

     In such a case you should use new batteries.

   If you own a tool by Akai, Blaupunkt, Fisher, Technics, Philips or
Sony you can be sure that they will work with the ir slave.


@EndNode

